{
  "masechta": "Sanhedrin",
  "daf": 6,
  "amud": "b",
  "macro_segments": [
    {
      "title": "The Debate Over Compromise (Peshara) versus Binding Judgment: Does Peshara Require a Kinyan?",
      "display_title": "Peshara & Kinyan",
      "timestamp": "00:50",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rav Ashi's inference that compromise does not require a kinyan from the dispute over whether one or three judges are needed",
          "display_title": "Rav Ashi: No Kinyan",
          "timestamp": "00:50"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Gemara's conclusion that peshara does in fact require a kinyan, and Tosafot's explanation of why three judges are still necessary despite the kinyan",
          "display_title": "Hilcheta: Kinyan Required",
          "timestamp": "02:12"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Dispute Between Rabbi Eliezer and Rabbi Yehoshua ben Korcha: Is Compromise Forbidden or a Mitzvah?",
      "display_title": "Eliezer vs. Yehoshua",
      "timestamp": "04:04",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The Gemara's baraita: compromise requires three judges just like judgment, and once judgment is rendered (gmar din) you cannot compromise",
          "display_title": "Baraita: 3 Judges, No Po…",
          "timestamp": "04:04"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Eliezer ben Rabbi Yose HaGalili's position that compromise is forbidden and perverts truth; contrast with Aharon's peacemaking before court",
          "display_title": "R. Eliezer: Assur",
          "timestamp": "04:47"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rashi's explanation that compromise is forbidden only once the case comes before the judges, not before litigation begins",
          "display_title": "Rashi: Before Court",
          "timestamp": "07:52"
        },
        {
          "title": "The tangent on one who steals and makes blessings, and Rabbi Meir's critique of Judah's compromise regarding Joseph",
          "display_title": "Stolen Goods & Judah",
          "timestamp": "08:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yehoshua ben Korcha's position that compromise is a mitzvah and a judgment that includes peace (mishpat shalom)",
          "display_title": "R. Yehoshua: Mitzva",
          "timestamp": "10:25"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Gemara's interpretation that David's judgment included tzedakah (righteousness) by helping the poor party after judgment was rendered",
          "display_title": "David's Tzedakah Model",
          "timestamp": "11:56"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Shimon ben Menasya's position: you can suggest compromise only before you know which way the judgment will lean",
          "display_title": "R. Shimon: Before Clarity",
          "timestamp": "17:56"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "When Can a Judge Recuse Himself? The Balance Between Personal Safety and Judicial Responsibility",
      "display_title": "Recusal & Responsibility",
      "timestamp": "21:50",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Reish Lakish's view that a judge may recuse himself (say 'I am not concerned with you') before knowing the direction of the judgment, but not after",
          "display_title": "Reish Lakish: Before Cla…",
          "timestamp": "21:50"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Gemara's citation of 'do not be afraid of any man' to show that once judgment is clear, the judge cannot step away",
          "display_title": "'Lo Taguru' Obligation",
          "timestamp": "24:05"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Responsibility of Witnesses and Judges to Pursue Truth and Justice Before God",
      "display_title": "Witnesses & Judges",
      "timestamp": "24:22",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yehoshua ben Korcha's ruling that even a student sitting before the Rebbe must speak up if there is merit for the poor party or evidence against the rich party",
          "display_title": "Student Must Speak",
          "timestamp": "24:22"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Chanina's principle that one must not withhold their words because of fear of any person",
          "display_title": "Don't Withhold Words",
          "timestamp": "25:18"
        },
        {
          "title": "The heavy responsibility of witnesses: they must know whom they testify for, before whom, and who will exact payment (God); God stands in the congregation of judges",
          "display_title": "Witness Awareness",
          "timestamp": "25:38"
        },
        {
          "title": "The judge's responsibility: the fear that comes from knowing God is present and will exact judgment; but assurance that God is with the judge who acts with integrity",
          "display_title": "Judge's Fear & Assurance",
          "timestamp": "27:00"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Definition of Gmar Din and the Halacha Ruling on Compromise",
      "display_title": "Gmar Din & Ruling",
      "timestamp": "28:40",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "The definition of gmar din: when the judges declare 'you are liable' and 'you are exempt' — at that point compromise is forbidden",
          "display_title": "Gmar Din Definition",
          "timestamp": "28:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "The halacha rules like Rabbi Yehoshua ben Korcha that compromise is a mitzvah, but the Gemara clarifies this means the judge should offer it as an equal option (not actively push it)",
          "display_title": "Halacha: Equal Option",
          "timestamp": "29:12"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Huna's practice of asking litigants whether they want 'din' (judgment) or 'pshara' (compromise) as equal possibilities",
          "display_title": "Rav Huna's Practice",
          "timestamp": "29:34"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Gemara's distinction between Rabbi Yehoshua ben Korcha (who says compromise is a mitzvah to suggest) and the Tanna Kamma (who says it is only permissible if they ask)",
          "display_title": "Mitzvah vs. Permitted",
          "timestamp": "30:05"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Rabbi Tanchum bar Chanilai's View: The Verse About Compromise Refers to Aharon's Compromise at the Golden Calf, Not Judicial Compromise",
      "display_title": "Golden Calf Compromise",
      "timestamp": "34:08",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Tanchum bar Chanilai argues that the verse 'one who makes a compromise blesses and blasphemes God' refers to Aharon's compromise regarding the golden calf, not compromise in court",
          "display_title": "Tanchum: Egel Context",
          "timestamp": "34:08"
        },
        {
          "title": "The midrash and Gemara's reading of Aharon's decision: seeing Chur killed, Aharon reasoned that allowing the golden calf was preferable to being killed himself, as it left room for repentance",
          "display_title": "Aharon's Reasoning",
          "timestamp": "34:57"
        },
        {
          "title": "The other tannaim who interpret the verse 'one who releases water is the beginning of strife' as referring to Torah study (water = Torah) and personal judgment",
          "display_title": "Water = Torah",
          "timestamp": "37:08"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Folk Sayings and Divine Justice: Samual's Citings of Verses to Validate Common Aphorisms",
      "display_title": "Folk Sayings & Verses",
      "timestamp": "38:51",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Various folk sayings and aphorisms about conflict, patience, love, and faith, matched by Shmuel to biblical verses",
          "display_title": "Aphorisms Cited",
          "timestamp": "38:51"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Huna's teaching about God's presence with us: originally God's Shechina was within ten tefachim of the ground, but after sin, God could not even dwell in the thirty-amah-high Temple",
          "display_title": "Shechina Withdrawal",
          "timestamp": "44:49"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Gemara's conclusion on the meaning of 'lo taguru' (do not be afraid): it means to gather in or not withhold your words, with various source interpretations",
          "display_title": "'Lo Taguru' Meaning",
          "timestamp": "46:02"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
